The thorn-vines here have grown to an unusual height but failed to arch overhead, leaving the passage open to a sky now visible as a narrow strip — purple-grey, overcast, threaded with the shadows of the topmost vine branches.  The strip of sky does nothing for navigation and everything for despair: the Briar Maze extends as far as can be seen in every direction, an unbroken sea of brambles with no visible structure from above.  The lower vine-walls here drip a clear fluid from their thorn-tips, collecting in small pools on the path that smell of nothing but taste, apparently, of regret.~
