#1075
The Gnarled Root Gate~
The forest floor levels here at the top of a slope that descends abruptly into a different landscape — the bog visible beyond smells of sulphur and methane, and the air above it is visibly different in colour and consistency from the blighted but essentially terrestrial Blightwood.  Between the forest and the bog's edge stands the gnarled root gate: two massive roots from adjacent trees, each as thick as a horse's body, which have arched over the path and grown together overhead in a living portcullis of wood.  The gate's roots are covered in thorns the length of fingers, and thin tendrils of vine connect the arch to the ground on both sides, completing the barrier.  The root gate can be forced open — the tendrils must be broken, the weight of the arch pushed through — but it presses closed again on its own within minutes, a slow, organic insistence on remaining shut.~
