#1146
The Root Circle South~
The ancient oak's root system surfaces in this southern section in a series of massive arches that divide the space into natural chambers.  The moss here is deeper than in the northern sections, and the wildflowers denser, as if the sanctum's life-force concentrates toward its core.  The spring's outflow trickles through this section in a series of small channels carved by long use, the water catching the green-tinted light and carrying it southward.  The feeling of being watched from the trees is intense here — benevolent once, now indeterminate.~
